ial, environmental, and civil-military dimensions of this binational program. From the corridors of power in Washington and Ottawa to everyday life at the small outposts, The Joint Arctic Weather Stations explores delicate statecraft, changing scientific practices, as well as the distinctive station cultures that emerged as humans coped with isolation in polar environments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational law. 0aMeteorological stationszCanada, NorthernxHistoryy20th century. 0aMeteorological stations. 0aScience and statezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aScience and statezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aScience and state. 7aHISTORY / Polar Regions.2bisacsh  aCanada-US relations.  aanthropology of science.  aarctic history.  aarctic logistics.  acircumpolar studies.  acold war.  acultures of isolation.  adiplomacy.  aenvironmental history.  ahistorical geography.  ahistory of science.  aliving in isolation.  ameteorological science.  ameteorology.  apolar geography.  apolar history.  apolar logistics.  ascience diplomacy.  ascientists.  asocial history.  asovereignty.  aweather studies.1 aLackenbauer, P. Whitney, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781773852591?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781773852591423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781773852591/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles